    nursingActions: ["Match pharmacotherapy to IBS subtype: IBS-D = antispasmodics, TCAs, rifaximin, eluxadoline; IBS-C = linaclotide, lubiprostone; this distinction is critical for treatment success","Start TCAs at low dose for neuromodulation (NOT antidepressant dose): amitriptyline 10mg QHS, titrate by 10mg every 2-4 weeks to max 50mg; onset of effect 4-8 weeks for pain","Verify gallbladder status before prescribing eluxadoline: CONTRAINDICATED in patients post-cholecystectomy (pancreatitis risk from sphincter of Oddi spasm); document verification","Prescribe rifaximin with proper expectations: 550mg TID x 14 days; response may take 2-4 weeks after completion; can be repeated up to 2x for relapse; ~44% sustained response","Enroll patients in REMS program for alosetron: restricted to severe IBS-D in women only; requires signed patient-physician agreement; monitor for constipation and ischemic colitis symptoms","Counsel on linaclotide timing: take on empty stomach 30 min before first meal; constipation relief within 1 week; pain relief may take 4-6 weeks; primary side effect is diarrhea (dose-related)"],
